2.4 \FQC Derivation: Phase Alignment and Renormalization
The Quantum Coherence Function (\FQC) is derived from demanding that the effective field theory be perturbatively renormalizable while respecting the self-similarity requirement \mathcal{S} \to \mathcal{S}^{-1}.
 * Renormalization Group (RG) Flow: ESQET requires that the RG flow has a fixed point at \mathcal{S} = \phi. This is achieved by ensuring that the running coupling constant \lambda(\mu) is invariant under discrete scale transformations.
 * Phase Term: The complex phase terms in \FQC (involving \mathcal{D}_{\text{ent}} and \mathcal{T}_{\text{vac}}) emerge as the unique way to satisfy the RG constraints while maintaining locality and coupling the field \mathcal{S} to the vacuum's informational content (entanglement \mathcal{D}_{\text{ent}}).
 * Coherence Expression: The absolute value and subtraction \left[ 1 - \phi^{-1} |\dots| \right] ensure that \FQC \in [0, 1] and that \FQC reaches its maximal value (1) precisely when the entanglement and vacuum phases are aligned according to golden-ratio multiples.
